ir cities running. Working in public transit is a difficult job now, as it was a century ago. The benefits and decent wages Philadelphia public transit workers secured—advances that were hard-won and well deserved—came as a result of fighting for decades against their exploitation. Given capital’s great power in American society and management's enduring quest to control its workforce, it is remarkable to see how much Philadelphia’s transit workers achieved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIndustrial relationszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistory. 0aLocal transitzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistory. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies.  aPhiladelphia, public transportation system, welfare capitalism, public transit, labor force.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170423940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501704239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501704239/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016